ted or permitted by the government of that state. Humanitarian intervention can be seen as a moral duty to protect but it is also subject to misuse as a front for imperialism without regard to international law.In Humanitarian Intervention, the contributors explore the many questions surrounding the issue. Is humanitarian intervention permitted by international law? If not, is it nevertheless morally permissible or morally required? Realistically, might not the main consequence of the humanitarian intervention principle be that powerful states will coerce weak ones for purposes of their own? The current debate is updated by two innovations in particular, the first being the shift of emphasis from the permissibility of intervening to the responsibility to intervene, and the second an emerging conviction that the response to humanitarian crises needs to be collective, coordinated, and preemptive. The authors shed light on the timely debate of when and how to intervene and when, if ever, not to.Contributors: Carla Bagnoli, Joseph Boyle, Anthony Coates, Thomas Franck, Brian D. Lepard, Catherine Lu, Pratap Bhanu Mehta, Terry Nardin, Thomas Pogge, Melissa S. Williams, and Kok-Chor Tan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHumanitarian interventionvCongresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBagnoli, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyle, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoates, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranck, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLepard, Brian D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLu, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeht